Looking at `WorkerBindings.java`:
```java
    static DispatchBinding current(GenerationRegistry registry) {
        GenerationLease activeLease = registry.active();
        DispatchBinding binding = ACTIVE.get();
        if (binding == null) {
            DispatchBinding created = new DispatchBinding(activeLease);
            ACTIVE.set(created);
            return created;
        }

        if (!binding.matches(activeLease)) {
            DispatchBinding replacement = new DispatchBinding(activeLease);
            ACTIVE.set(replacement);
            return replacement;
        }

        return binding;
    }
```
When a new generation is loaded, `binding.matches(activeLease)` will be false. A new `DispatchBinding` is created and set to the `ThreadLocal`. However, the old `binding` is never closed! 

`DispatchBinding`'s constructor calls `lease.retain()`, so the old lease's reference count is never decremented when it's replaced in the `ThreadLocal`. This prevents the old `LoadedGeneration` (and its `URLClassLoader`) from being closed, leading to the Metaspace leak.
Plan: 1. Modify `src/main/java/io/harbor/textd/core/WorkerBindings.java` to close the old `DispatchBinding` before replacing it in the `ThreadLocal`.
2. Run the stress test again to verify the fix.

